content: Nice to see all of you here!
Before we begin with our study part,

casar, shuwang, SamSite, fallnavy, Xespok, virag, tunnet99, tianxia, strul, dhalsim, concord2497, mayhem, yzhnie, luwenzhe, smallpig, imaccn, Liuchao, whte, mikn1, yun_shou, dittp, ouyang, sosei, coco_yuang, HEX77.
Today, we will talk about another world famous player,
hmm, which country is he from?
team world champion, USSR champion, Russia champion, WC 4th place, lots of 1st places in international tournaments, 1st place in europe team in team intarnational tournament in Japan in 1991, etc.
tunnet always knows everything, he is my idiol
He lived in in USA for many years,
he was the best player in Russia
while he was away, many other players enjoyed the top of Russia, such as Klimashin, Sinyov, etc
When he came back from USA, he was not in same good shape as he used to be,
and he got many losses in his comeback tournament
but little by little he is getting back his old strength
and people will soon fear him as they feared him before
My first game with Kozhin was in 1989,
it was a draw, if I remember right.
1989 was the year of first WC,
Sutpid me, you didnt play in 1989
3 people from USSR, including Kozhin took part
and some weeks later, there was another tournament, in Russia,
my first game with him was 10 years later, also draw =)
and then I could meet him, a legendary Kozhin, so scary for me
So, I always remember my first feeling when I met such great star like Kozhin.
In years, Kozhin and I have met so many times that I lose the count.
Kozhin used to be one of the fans of i12 opening, too.
I remember, he set the i12 opening against me in Russia tournament in year..... umm... 1997?
and I won that one as black.
in Russian QT for the WC 2003
the first thing that always comes to my mind is..
my loss to Nara in WC 97
In WC 97 the move 11-f6 became popular.
by the way, I forgot to metion one important fact.
Have you heard of the book "Click of stones"?
Kozhin is the author of it
contain some mistake as i heard
In Kozhin's book, such 15th move was introduced,
And after this 16th - no win for black
So, it confused the players who didnt deeply analysed this variant themselves,
assuming black is not good after all,
who thought black doesnt have win
and then, when I saw the right winning 15th move,
I realized how stupid I was.
Then after 1997, this variant disappeared from tournament practice for 4-5 years..
As you know the saying "everything is is the forgotten old"
People, seeing this 12th move were sure they had found all wins back in 1997,
because no articles were published about it,
So, the 12th move was a success last year,
making many black players to fail,
and some even altered the black path,
However, some serious masters, including Kozhin, seems to have taken it as a serious challenge,
and did not avoid playing it as black.
This game we are about to see, will reveal the truth behind this 12th move.

tianxia, tunnet99, virag, luwenzhe, SamSite, shuwang, dhalsim, imaccn, Fermat, mayhem, Xespok, lingdodo, yzhnie, strul, casar, smallpig, leto, sosei, concord2497, ouyang, mikn1, Intotherenju, whte, Liuchao, dittp, coco_yuang, weigui, moocheng.
Semyonov chose the left side for defense.
it clears the ideas a lot
Indeed, this is an important timing.
you saw what happens if you leave it for "too late"
who can show win after such 20th move? say me
you can even say "me" if you dont see the win yet, but you would like to try
then the next one can say me
bu磘 wait that 24 was black win
please say "me" instead of suggesting single moves
because, suggesting moves is like a guessing game,
maybe you say, but you actually dont take it seriously
but if "me", then you will actually have to submit it
my hope is that when someone is on "me", then let him try alone, until some result...
evrybody know there are two possibilities d8 or d11, lingdodo :)
because he will get less joy if he just follows someone elses hints
go on or give up tunnet
you will let someone else try then?
there is a goto move option:)
Kozhin did not have to face these difficulties however,
because his opponent thought that the upper 20th move is even better for white.
black have more strength lower now
What can you say about 22nd move?
i hope to hear everybody's comment this time
we need investigate 3 point rule about four
D9 would leave VCF for black ?
and not to fear to black take it
i mean, if 24-D9, then black VCF
semyonov feared black would play e5 g6 d7 f9
but I can not find win from so many four
and then white should close the three from down and maybe upper side would be dangouros.. maybe no win but scary and semyonov didn't wan't to face these difciculties
is e5 g6 d7 f9 scary?
white can do it when necessary, then no need now
I guess white is better now
no vct? so black gas to defend at the bottom
tunnet's explanation is good, Semyonov, knowing his abilities, did not even try to calculate what follows from this point on,
so he just decided to simplify things by playing the white four first.
But if such game happened in WC finals,
then the white player would probably spend long time,
I do not think it is a win
and make sure about the black attack,
but the question is, this white four bad or good?
and as a result, then decide about using the four.
virag - if the four can be unplayed, then the four was bad move
if no win, it is bad. otherwise it is good
so we are checking the 3rd condition here, fearing the opponent taking the four point,
white gets the final tempo from e2,
and you must make decision here,
So, even we realized that actually white didnt have to use the four,
but it was very logical move, from white's aspect
This is how Kozhin attacked, beautiful attack!
If 34 here, who will show the win?
how about strul, also ready to show?
no based on old idee txs

20 on other side is also difficult maybe =)
maybe you could go through it slowly
and made black win very easy.
It was a very interesting game.
However, the move 20 remains a question.
And your homework will be to put some light on the other 20th move.
Still, it seems there is easier win for black.
And it begins with this 19th move!
who would want to be black?
if we kill this 22nd move, then all other 22nd moves are easy already
yep, good, and now the other branch too
maybe we let others try it
if i would've stopped to think it, we'd continue the lesson even tomorrow :)
strul is strong enough to win by himself
So, what we learned from this game was the powerful attack style by Kozhin.
Even without having theoretical preparation about recent theories,
he used his remarkable skill and talent,
to make a long and beautiful attack,
Such great man as Kozhin doesnt need to know theory.
He can invent win moves across the board!
but it seems he made wrong attack in 19th
about 19, you will prove if it was good or not.
But now, we will end our lesson. I thank you so much for coming here and being active today! It was fun lesson!
